<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Soda Process" class="currentChild" href="Soda_Process">Soda Process</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
An alkaline <a title="Chemical Pulping" href="Chemical_Pulping">chemical pulping</a> process in which wood chips are digested in a caustic soda containing lye (NaOH), produced by adding <a title="Sodium Carbonate" href="Sodium_Carbonate">sodium carbonate</a> (Na<sub>2</sub>CO3) to lime (CaO). The soda process is useful for digesting <a title="Softwood" href="Softwood">softwood</a> or <a title="Hardwood" href="Hardwood">hardwood</a>. The first commercial production of soda pulp was in 1851, and is used infrequently in the present-day due to the superiority of newer processes. In 1879, sodium sulfate (Na<sub>2</sub>SO4) was added to the soda process, and a much stronger pulp resulted. This process, dubbed the <a title="Sulfate Process" href="Sulfate_Process">sulfate process</a>, replaced the traditional soda process, although it was found later that the ingredient primarily responsible for the increased strength wasn't sodium sulfate, but sodium sul'fide<em> (Na<sub>2</sub>S). The sulfate process is also called the <a title="Kraft" href="Kraft">kraft</a> (after the German and Swedish word for "strength") process and is the most prevalent chemical pulpng system currently in use. 
</p>
<p id="l3">
Pulps produced using the soda process are called <a title="Soda Pulp" href="Soda_Pulp">soda pulp</a>. (See also <a title="Pulping" href="Pulping">Pulping</a> and <a title="Chemical Pulping" href="Chemical_Pulping">Chemical Pulping</a>.) 
</p>
